	"title": "Les verbes pronominaux — Reflexive verbs",
	"objective": "Describe your daily routine in detail using reflexive verbs (A2: can describe routines and habits).",
	"bridge": {
		"title": "Bridge from Hindi / English: the “self” pronoun comes before the verb",
		"body": "Reflexive verbs carry a pronoun that refers back to the subject: **je me lève** (I get [myself] up), **il se lave** (he washes [himself]). English often hides this (“I get up”), so don’t forget the **me / te / se / nous / vous / se** — and it goes **before** the verb. Think of Hindi’s खुद / अपने को. Order: subject + reflexive pronoun + verb.",
		"quiz": {
			"prompt": "What is the main bridge idea for \"Les verbes pronominaux — Reflexive verbs\"?",
			"options": [
				"Focus on: the “self” pronoun comes before the verb",
				"Ignore grammar gender entirely",
				"Only practise numbers, never verbs"
			],
			"answerIndex": 0
		}
	},
